Let's create a simple class called 'Dog'. In this class, we will define two attributes: 'name' and 'age', and one method called 'bark'. Here’s how it looks in Java:

class Dog {
    String name; // This is an attribute for the dog's name
    int age; // This is an attribute for the dog's age

    void bark() { // This is a method that makes the dog bark
        System.out.println(name + " says Woof!");
    }
}

In this example, we define a class 'Dog' with two attributes: 'name' and 'age'. The 'bark' method prints a message that includes the dog's name. To create a 'Dog' object, you would write:

Dog myDog = new Dog();
myDog.name = "Buddy";
myDog.age = 3;
myDog.bark();

This code creates a new Dog object named 'myDog', sets its name to 'Buddy', and calls the 'bark' method, which outputs 'Buddy says Woof!'.

Let's create a class called 'Student'. This class will have attributes for 'name' and 'grade', and a method to display the student's information. Here’s how it looks in Java:

class Student {
    String name; // Attribute for the student's name
    int grade; // Attribute for the student's grade

    void displayInfo() { // Method to display student information
        System.out.println("Name: " + name + ", Grade: " + grade);
    }
}

To create a 'Student' object, you would write:

Student student1 = new Student();
student1.name = "Alice";
student1.grade = 10;
student1.displayInfo();

This code creates a new Student object named 'student1', sets its name to 'Alice', and its grade to 10. When you call 'displayInfo()', it outputs 'Name: Alice, Grade: 10'.
